  <static seed="1256" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/addSubtractRationalExpressions70.pg">
    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{1}{x-3}-\frac{6}{x^{2}-9}} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{1}{x+3}, x\ne 3</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{1}{x-3}-\frac{6}{x^{2}-9}} 
      \amp = {\frac{1}{x-3}}-\frac{6}{(x - 3)(x + 3)} \\
      \amp = \frac{1\cdot({x+3})}{({x-3})\cdot({x+3})} -\frac{6}{(x - 3)(x + 3)} \\
      \amp = \frac{{x+3-6}}{(x - 3)(x + 3)} \\
      \amp = \frac{{x-3}}{(x - 3)(x + 3)} \\
      \amp = {\frac{1}{x+3}, x\ne 3}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>{x-3}</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>x \ne {3}</m>.</p>
</solution>
